We will calculate each ratio step by step using the end‐of‐period values from the provided statements.

1. Current Ratio  
 • Total Current Assets = 7,664,945.72  
 • Total Current Liabilities = 2,736,025.72  
  Current Ratio = 7,664,945.72 / 2,736,025.72 ≈ 2.80  

2. Gross Profit Margin  
 • Gross Profit = 1,340,513.79  
 • Total Revenue = 6,920,513.79  
  Gross Profit Margin = (1,340,513.79 / 6,920,513.79) × 100% ≈ 19.36%

3. Debt to Asset Ratio  
 • Here the only liabilities given are the current liabilities: 2,736,025.72  
 • Total Assets = 14,066,175.95  
  Debt to Asset Ratio = 2,736,025.72 / 14,066,175.95 ≈ 0.19

4. Net Profit Margin  
 • Net Profit = –1,669,849.77  
 • Total Revenue = 6,920,513.79  
  Net Profit Margin = (–1,669,849.77 / 6,920,513.79) × 100% ≈ –24.12%

5. Cash to Current Debt Ratio  
 • Cash and Cash Equivalents (Ending Balance) = 838,919.82  
 • Total Current Liabilities = 2,736,025.72  
  Cash to Current Debt Ratio = 838,919.82 / 2,736,025.72 ≈ 0.31

6. Free Cash Flow (FCF)  
 • FCF is typically defined as Cash Flow from Operating Activities minus Capital Expenditure (or plus Net Cash Flow from Investing Activities if all investing cash is capex).  
 • Here: Operating Cash Flow = –5,714,107.45  
  Investing Cash Flow = –1,446,972.73  
  FCF = –5,714,107.45 + (–1,446,972.73) = –7,161,080.18

7. Return on Assets (ROA)  
 • ROA = (Net Profit / Total Assets) × 100%  
  = (–1,669,849.77 / 14,066,175.95) × 100% ≈ –11.87%

Putting it all together, the solution is:

    "Cash to Current Debt Ratio": "0.31",
    "Free Cash Flow (FCF)": "-7161080.18",
    "Return on Assets (ROA)": "-11.87%"
  }
}
